1 patient volume, crime rates in the community, and the availability of law
2 enforcement to respond to violent incidents at the hospital.
3 (3) The security plan shall include an option for health care employees
4 who provide direct patient care to request an identification badge containing
5 only their first name or their first name and last initial.
6 (4)(A) The security plan shall require at least one hospital employee
7 trained in de-escalation strategies to be present at all times in the hospital’s
8 emergency department and all other patient care areas.
9 (B) The security plan shall require that a hospital employee trained in
10 trauma-informed care and victim support serve as a liaison to law enforcement,
11 support victims through the legal process, and ensure that the response to
12 incidents of violence at the hospital prioritize the safety and retention of
13 hospital employees providing health care services to the extent permitted under
14 State and federal law.
15 (5) The security plan shall establish training requirements for
16 appropriate hospital employees on the following:
17 (A) the culture of safety as determined by the hospital;
18 (B) response to the presence or use of weapons;
19 (C) defensive tactics;
20 (D) de-escalation techniques;
21 (E) appropriate physical restraint and seclusion techniques;
