1 (F) crisis intervention;
2 (G) trauma-informed care and strategies;
3 (H) clinician well-being practices;
4 (I) presence and intervention of law enforcement; and
5 (J) safely addressing situations involving patients, family members,
6 or other individuals who pose a risk of self-harm or harm to others.
7 (6) The security plan shall include guidelines indicating when a law
8 enforcement officer should remain with a patient who has demonstrated
9 violence or harm to others. The guidelines shall be developed jointly by a
10 health care provider representative and law enforcement.
11 (7)(A) A hospital shall review and evaluate the security plan developed
12 pursuant to this subsection annually in conjunction with the data collected
13 pursuant to subdivision (b)(3) of this section. If necessary, the hospital shall
14 revise the security plan.
15 (B) The security plan and any annual revisions to the security plan
16 shall be distributed annually to all hospital employees, volunteers, the
17 hospital’s board of directors, relevant law enforcement agencies, and any other
18 partners identified by the security plan development team.
19 (b)(1) A hospital licensed pursuant to this chapter shall establish and utilize
20 a workplace violence incident reporting system to document, track, analyze,
21 and evaluate incidents of workplace violence at the hospital. Data collection
